[2
Date: Wed, 21 Jul 1999 17:33:18 -0400
From: Dorothy Preslar <dpreslar@fas.org>
Source: Itar-Tass, Tribuna, Agence France-Presse and Moscow News, 21 Jul
1999 [edited

News sources in Russia today issued reports on outbreaks of a hemorraghic
fever in the Rostov and Stavropol regions. While the identity of the fever
is not yet confirmed, Anatoly Lepnitsky, Professor and Deputy Director of
the Volgograd Center for Disease Control, said that examinations of samples
have shown the presence of Congo-Crimean hemorrhagic fever in 23 out of 28
persons tested.
The outbreak began two weeks ago in the village of Oblivskaya, killing 6 and
hospitalizing at least 136. A second outbreak in the neighboring Stavropol
region has claimed 3 lives out of 7 cases in the villages of Neftekumsk and
Ipatovo.
There have been no additional cases in the past 24 hours in Oblivskaya,
where land is being treated with special disinfectants against insects and
rodents. Itar-Tass reported that the use of a new antiviral medicine is
being proposed by Alexander Lelyak, head of a medical research center in
Novosibirsk. The medicine, Vetom1.1 is said to be able to "subdue a wide
range of pathogenic viruses." It is certfied for veterinary use only but
"is equally effective for all the warm-blooded."
In Stavropol, Health Minister Nikolai Shibkov told Tass that a special
support laboratory would be opened at the Stavropol Anti-Plague Research
Centre in the Budyonnovsk district. In the meanwhile, diagnostic tests are
being run at the Moscow Institute of Virology.
The initial symptoms appeared to be flu-like: high temperature, rheumatic
pains and headache. Later symptoms include vomiting, coma, a plague-like
skin rash, internal bleeding and even fatal brain hemorrhaging.
Doctors believe the outbreak started on 5 July 1999 and that there is
aerosol
transmission via saliva droplets.
News of the outbreaks has, according to the Moscow News report, been slowly
seeping out of the districts, despite a "gag order" and quarantine. This
news service also said that the administrator of the Oblivskaya Internet
service, on 12 Jul 1999 posted information on the epidemic on a web site,
URL and that the server was closed several days
later.
All sources report announcements that the situation is under control and the
epidemic is waning. However, Anatoly Monisov, a department chief at the
Russian State Sanitation and Epidemiology Inspectorate said "It is
disturbing that we cannot identify the virus." Results of tests being run
at the Moscow Institute, he said, will not be available for a month.
---
