[This is all rather confusing:
Minister Gennadij Onischenk is quoted as saying on TV that 65/136 people
hospitalized in the Rostov region "had clinical symptoms similar to
Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever, " but Prof. Elena Leschinskaya is quoted in
the press as saying that "the clinical picture of the disease is not typical
for ... CCHF."
Prof. Anatoly Lepnitsky is quoted in the press as saying that "examinations
of samples have shown the presence of Congo-Crimean hemorrhagic fever in 23
out of 28 persons tested," (it not being clear if that means virus
isolation, virus detection by PCR, or antibody detection), yet Anatoly
Monisov is quoted in the press as saying "It is disturbing that we cannot
identify the virus," & that results of tests being run at the Moscow
Institute will not be available for a month."
It is easy to isolate & identify CCHF virus -- I was the first to describe
it from a blood specimen from the then Belgian Congo, & Jordi Casals
identified it in the old Rockefeller Foundation Virus Labs in New York back
in the early 1960s. I am thrilled that Lepnitsky called it Congo-Crimean
hemorrhagic fever, its true name, because back during the Cold War the
Soviets insisted on registering it, against all the rules, as
Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever!
Maybe both things are true: there were 23 people with CCHF and a lot more
people with something else so far unidentified - Mod.JW
